I just marked this in one file to give an example, could you go through all your changes and adopt code names, please?'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-10-24 07:20:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: (3 inline comments)

Hi Andrea,

I did as you said, because I would like this patch to get approved, so I can go on and continue my work on this documentation (yes, I'm planning on writing more, this is only the first step). Though I really think it's the wrong approach here. I'm really talking about configuring packages, in the Debian context, as in the config (prompting questions to our users) and postinst (doing the actual configuration work) scripts being called. If I write:

As for the rest of OpenStack, the Block Storage service is configured through debconf.

it looses the fact that we are configuring *packages* here (in this case, cinder-common). I'd be tempted to rather explicitely write:

As for the rest of OpenStack, the <application>cinder-common</application> and <application>cinder-api</application> Debian packages are configured through the debconf configuration system.

This way, I would keep the conventions, and inform our users of which package will prompt for debconf configuration questions.

Your thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-10-24 07:21:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-24 07:26:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Works for me

Thomas, you're right - this was in before."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2013-10-25 13:53:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 6772, 'date': '2013-10-25 20:41:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(6 inline comments)

I commented on specific instances inline but rather than go through the rest I will put a TL;DR.

When adding a note that is specific to Debian I don't believe there is a need to include Ubuntu in the OS profile, instead you can just set os="debian".

This will facilitate us (or someone from the Debian community) building and distributing a debian only version of the guide if they ever want to.

These conditionals will also still be picked up in the current setup where the guide builds with "ubuntu;debian" because the way profiling works in DocBook this will pick up elements that are marked for ubuntu OR debian. The reason we use both most of the time is because there is no difference, but where there is a difference it should use the more specific profiling condition.

Additionally in most places the debian specific stuff has been implemented as notes, some of which are quite unwieldy. I would prefer to see them broken up a bit, perhaps into steps or substeps with a title highlighting that they are for Debian.'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-10-26 06:42:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: (6 inline comments)

Hi Stephen,

Thanks for pointing out that currently we do ubuntu OR debian when generating the doc. I was wondering myself about this.

I have reviewed my patch, and wrote "debian" only when it was only specific to Debian.

I currently do believe that it'd be great to have a Debian specific generation of this doc. I would like to add some screenshots of the debconf questions, which looks a bit overkill in the current format (it will bother Ubuntu users). My idea was to do a chapter specific to the Debconf part of the Debian packages. You can see what I did for Folsom over here:

https://wiki.debian.org/OpenStackHowto/Folsom

the idea is to have the same kinds of snapshots to illustrate the installation. I would also like to write about preseeding, since that's one of the very cool feature of debconf as well.

If I do what I just described just above, then it will really make a lot of sense to have 2 separate generated docs, one for Ubuntu, and one for Debian.

Though could we please delay the discussion after this first patch gets in? I think it is more urgent to have at least some Debian support which is really lacking, rather to have a perfect result right away.'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-10-26 06:44:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-26 06:50:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Works for me

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-25 19:39:07.000000000', 'message': 'Simplify callers of diskfile.[read|write]_metadata()

As it happens, diskfile.read_metadata() and diskfile.write_metadata()
can take either an open file or a filename as their first arguments
(since xattr.[get|set]xattr() can), so we can clean up a couple places
where we were opening a file just to call read_metadata() or
write_metadata() on it. This results in 2 fewer system calls.

Example strace output:

/* read_metadata(filename) */
getxattr("/mnt/sdb1/1/node/sdb1/afile", "user.some.key", 0x0, 0) = 10
getxattr("/mnt/sdb1/1/node/sdb1/afile", "user.some.key", "some-value", 10) = 10

/* fp = open(filename); read_metadata(fp) */
open("/mnt/sdb1/1/node/sdb1/afile", O_RDONLY) = 4
fstat(4, {st_mode=S_IFREG|0664, st_size=0, ...}) = 0
fgetxattr(4, "user.some.key", 0x0, 0)   = 10
fgetxattr(4, "user.some.key", "some-value", 10) = 10

Change-Id: I321d8663b9e9e47b8f3ee6c21a1b65b408bb80e6
'}]
commit_message:
Simplify callers of diskfile.[read|write]_metadata()

As it happens, diskfile.read_metadata() and diskfile.write_metadata()
can take either an open file or a filename as their first arguments
(since xattr.[get|set]xattr() can), so we can clean up a couple places
where we were opening a file just to call read_metadata() or
write_metadata() on it. This results in 2 fewer system calls.

Example strace output:

/* read_metadata(filename) */
getxattr("/mnt/sdb1/1/node/sdb1/afile", "user.some.key", 0x0, 0) = 10
getxattr("/mnt/sdb1/1/node/sdb1/afile", "user.some.key", "some-value", 10) = 10

/* fp = open(filename); read_metadata(fp) */
open("/mnt/sdb1/1/node/sdb1/afile", O_RDONLY) = 4
fstat(4, {st_mode=S_IFREG|0664, st_size=0, ...}) = 0
fgetxattr(4, "user.some.key", 0x0, 0)   = 10
fgetxattr(4, "user.some.key", "some-value", 10) = 10

Change-Id: I321d8663b9e9e47b8f3ee6c21a1b65b408bb80e6

commit_message:
Be more careful when passing result to revert()

Instead of passing result as separate keyword argument (which may
lead to strange TypeError exception) we put it to kwargs dict.

Change-Id: I899763e047badeadfd367aa1f06ba4cf6c1b0951

[{'created': '2013-10-25 01:46:38.000000000', 'message': "NVP: Correct NVP router port mac to match neutron

Previously when router ports were created the mac_address from neutron
was not passed to nvp so nvp generated it's own mac_address for the port.
This patch fixes this by passing the mac_address on the port to nvp.

Fixes bug: 1244481

Change-Id: I0d0e068923497a13915749f3781d54194cfcfe89
"}]
commit_message:
NVP: Correct NVP router port mac to match neutron

Previously when router ports were created the mac_address from neutron
was not passed to nvp so nvp generated it's own mac_address for the port.
This patch fixes this by passing the mac_address on the port to nvp.

Fixes bug: 1244481

Change-Id: I0d0e068923497a13915749f3781d54194cfcfe89

commit_message:
add BaseV2ComputeTest as the base class of nova v2 api tests

this does refactor in compute.base, add BaseV2ComputeTest as
the base class of nova v2 api test. Because there will be nova
v3 tests, this change will be convenient to add BaseV3ComputeTest
as the base class of nova v3 api tests. In this way, we can split
v2 tests with v3 tests easily, and share some common method.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: Ie8e0d17a95e8378733dd21ab341dfad1331edf6e

commit_message:
Enable Network Namespaces by Default for GRE

Previously, the instructions in the OVS GRE install guide
had network namespaces explicitly disabled, based on historical
documentation.  However, this is no longer valid.  Instructions
on disabling network namespaces have instead been moved to a general
note, and the instructions for enabling network namespaces have
been bumped up from the OVS VLAN-specific instructions to the
general OVS instructions.

Cherry-Picked from: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/53380/
Change-Id: Icd2ea7ffcf6f412d66efd1f46a386318ae74e135
Fixes: bug #1241056
backport: havana

commit_message:
Storwize: Fix iogrp availability check

Do not check if vdisk_count is greater than zero to determine iogrp
availability. This is wrong, and leads to the driver not being able to
use empty iogrps.

Closes-Bug: #1240395
Cherry-pick from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/52031/

Change-Id: I50456a0c618103f919ef0da7fb9e44b77a1d9bff

[{'created': '2013-10-19 07:29:57.000000000', 'message': 'Enable "cinder delete" can delete multiple volumes in one request

"nova delete" can delete multiple servers in one request but
"cinder delete" can only delete one volume in one request, it is
better to enhance cinder client to support remove multiple volumes
in one request.

Change-Id: I6a63aa3d7e4c152ae5e45bf2b36d862bdcd6df33
Closes-Bug: #1241941

commit_message:
Enable "cinder delete" can delete multiple volumes in one request

"nova delete" can delete multiple servers in one request but
"cinder delete" can only delete one volume in one request, it is
better to enhance cinder client to support remove multiple volumes
in one request.

Change-Id: I6a63aa3d7e4c152ae5e45bf2b36d862bdcd6df33
Closes-Bug: #1241941

"}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-10-12 16:41:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks Dan, one question, if we get the hostname truncated, it might cause some hostname same, comments?

Also want to double confirm, do you mean that we need to truncated hostname in compute/api.py:_populate_instance_names()?'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-10-12 17:03:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Do not merge

You're making the assumption that the display_name turns into the DNS name, which is only the case on nova-network, AFAICT. Plus, DNS names *can* be duplicated. Not only that, but linux, windows, and other OSes have different limits (windows is 15 or 20 characters depending on configuration, AFAICT). Limiting it to one OS's native limit means it will be wrong for all other guest OSes.

My point is that there may be environments (i.e. not using nova-network, using Moniker with custom DNS, etc) that might want a 255-character display_name and so we shouldn't limit it at the compute API layer.

Your second question: no, limiting instance.hostname to 64 characters is still wrong. The column is 255 characters, and as I said above, will be wrong for anything other than linux at that point.

The only place the hostname and display_name hits DNS (that I can see) is in nova-network, so if truncation needs to happen, it could be done there. HOWEVER, as far as I know, the RLL encoding of DNS names also has a limit of 255 characters per element, which means we should allow instances  and their DNS records to take that full length for the name, even if the guest inside (which we know nothing about) can't handle it.

So, I think I've convinced myself this is not something we should change in nova. I'm DnM for now."}, {'account_id': 6794, 'date': '2013-10-18 07:34:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I second Dan's comments here.

The only thing that needs to be done so far is making sure that nova-network generates a valid dhcp-hostsfile for dnsmasq. This means that the hostnames injected into dhcp-hostsfile MUST comply with RFC 1035:
- label length MUST be 63 or less
- name length MUST be 255 or less"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-26 06:03:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned

commit_message:
Raise error if server name exceeds 63 characters

The maximum hostname on Linux is 64 characters. DHCP is limited to
this host maximum. Unfortunately Nova allows the creation of servers
with names exceed 63 characters in length.

The fix was let nova api throw exceptions if server name exceeds
63 characters.

Change-Id: I06922e60c36ce5679bca6317e80c2686731dd7a8
Closes-Bug: #1238910

commit_message:
Adding IDH plugin basic implementation

Functionality:

* install and provision Intel Hadoop Manager and Intel Hadoop
* configure Intel Hadoop to use Cinder volumes as HDFS backend
* manual cluster scaling support
* Swift integration
* cluster configs - the same configs as in Vanilla Hadoop
* configs validation - the same as in Vanilla plugin

Implements blueprint idh-savanna-plugin

Change-Id: I4ca3063481a26facd6288a439d3339baf25d9972

commit_message:
Fix Hive for EDP work

 *  While the job is submitting to oozie,
 hive-site requires to add swift auth
 properties and only after that it should
 be copied to hdfs

Implements blueprint edp-vanilla-plugin-hive-pig

Change-Id: Id9814147e832578c36a1b7c2b4ed817c240662da

At keystone's start, a call to install() in the module gettextutils
sets _ globally as the localization function. This means that _ is

commit_message:
set l10n function if importing outside of keystone

At keystone's start, a call to install() in the module gettextutils
sets _ globally as the localization function. This means that _ is
set without the need of importing it from gettextutils. However,
importing a keystone module that uses _ outside of keystone will
result in a NameError exception.

This fixes bug #1241000

Change-Id: If384abc588e0a4f10d18cb077185eb25323e5723

commit_message:
Use app.logger in auth_token

On some systems in Swift we see no logging from auth_token if
log_name is set to anything at all. It may be more correct to
educate operators not to configure it that way, but there's a
bunch of recipies floating around that set log_name among other
logging parameters.

Not sure if this is an excellent solution, but let's try and
use app.logger if available. This needs to be checked with Nova
et.al for compatibility.

Fixes bug 1202456
Change-Id: I83520b5868ae3995c8b84c47e779a2b31294d361

commit_message:
Add EC2 CredentialsManager to v3 client

The EC2 extension is in the default Keystone pipeline for
Grizzly and Havana. It's already used by Horizon but missing support
in the client causes failures when using v3.

Change-Id: I8d3c9c6fb1d530a051af812cecc0097fa6db1574
Closes-bug: #1236326

Otherwise errors can be very difficult to track down,
because nothing is printed.  See for example bug #1178233

commit_message:
Add unit tests for glance/common/client.py

I have omitted tests in this commit for seekable() and image_iterator()
based on the fact they rely on a broken sendfile implementation which I
feel should be fixed as part of a separate commit (bug 1206845).

Fixes bug 1115551

Change-Id: If58b90a189ba675ddc890f339659f5d1b59c33a3

commit_message:
Utilizes assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone

Using assertEqual/assertNotEqual to test if an element
is or is not None is too python2.4.
Our unit testing framework supports assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone
which were created for these types of tests.

Partial-bug: #1230028

Change-Id: Ie0bddae642f7973ee8b0e00164415f8d87de387e

[{'created': '2013-10-25 08:41:12.000000000', 'message': "user-list Databases Value is JSON vs a String

changes the 'databases' value returned in user-list from json to
a string of comma separated values

$ trove user-list <instance_uuid>

before:
+------+------+-----------------------------------------------+
| name | host |                   databases                   |
+------+------+-----------------------------------------------+
| bob  |  %   |             [{u'name': u'monkey'}]            |
| tom  |  %   | [{u'name': u'freshdb'}, {u'name': u'monkey'}] |
+------+------+-----------------------------------------------+

after:
+------+------+-----------------+
| name | host |    databases    |
+------+------+-----------------+
| bob  |  %   |      monkey     |
| tom  |  %   | freshdb, monkey |
+------+------+-----------------+

Change-Id: I8e18e05b722be8a65a15f9ed15264d48d50ecc4e
Closes-Bug: #1238216
"}]
commit_message:
user-list Databases Value is JSON vs a String

changes the 'databases' value returned in user-list from json to
a string of comma separated values

$ trove user-list <instance_uuid>

before:
+------+------+-----------------------------------------------+
| name | host |                   databases                   |
+------+------+-----------------------------------------------+
| bob  |  %   |             [{u'name': u'monkey'}]            |
| tom  |  %   | [{u'name': u'freshdb'}, {u'name': u'monkey'}] |
+------+------+-----------------------------------------------+

after:
+------+------+-----------------+
| name | host |    databases    |
+------+------+-----------------+
| bob  |  %   |      monkey     |
| tom  |  %   | freshdb, monkey |
+------+------+-----------------+

Change-Id: I8e18e05b722be8a65a15f9ed15264d48d50ecc4e
Closes-Bug: #1238216

commit_message:
Simulates events so run_tests.py executes 10x faster

This restores some functionality that had been removed earlier to use
a class from Oslo. It turns out making it work with the new Oslo RPC
manager code wasn't too hard, plus the new version is hopefully easier
to follow.

Change-Id: I18e4d06359f28605cd764a10ace791997f534ed7
Implements: blueprint bring-back-event-simulator

commit_message:
Fix the testname of scenario

Duplicated testname in scenarios will result duplicated testname
by testscenarios, they can not be sorted in PY33 env, and will
induce TypeError:
TypeError: unorderable types: StackManagerNoPaginationTest() <
StackManagerNoPaginationTest()

Close-Bug #1243096

Change-Id: I4c02c9f3868495ec4399f795e864f26afc3d26b7

fix nvp version validation for distributed router creation

Fix typo on major version. This was not caught during unit tests
so adds a few to ensure this does not regress.

Fix bug #1243862

commit_message:
Add amqp=WARN,qpid=WARN to default_log_levels

The default value of default_log_levels includes amqplib=WARN.  However,
the kombu library uses an amqplib fork, amqp.  We were just recently
talking about how much of the debug log is full of amqp entries here:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-October/017379.html

so just suppress them by default, because most of the time, they are not
needed.

In passing, add qpid=WARN for the same reason.  Alphabetize the list,
too, just because I felt like it.

Change-Id: Ie7590ac1033adaadade799da2588f566110efddc

commit_message:
Early die if on image gets killed

The Images reaches the 'killed' status only on an
unrecoverable error, any further wait is in vain.

The wait method will raise an exception on the killed state.

Change-Id: I392674c872d7f2354a2a2d338e14630b211cf12b

commit_message:
Make test_nvp_sync.SyncLoopingCallTestCase reliable

This patch removes the previous check that verified the mocked
looping call had an exact number of calls, and replaces it with a
simpler check that just verifies that the mock has been called.

As a consequence, this patch also shortens the test duration.

Closes-Bug: 1241969

Change-Id: Ia7bc66e1f2f631e46ddcbe0eacc1d5b2481274cb

commit_message:
Install Guide: Fix bugs in block storage node

* Fix misspelled pvcreate command
* storage node needs cinder database password
* tgtd.conf must include cinder volume configs (rhel;centos;fedora)
* lvm filter wouldn't work with the volume used

backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1243671
(cherry picked from commit c9249bce213d6825d507c5fe15df700e1f2a3dd6)

Change-Id: I57a95cab59e3341fb74a99d5947fe54b906e32e1

commit_message:
Fix Misplaced Steps in OVS Setup

It would appear that some of the steps from the main Neutron setup
managed to find themselves in the OVS section.  This was rather
confusing to the reader, as the steps seemed to abruptly change
course in the OVS documentation, while the steps in the main Neutron
install guide seem to skip over discussing the plugin entirely.
This is now rectified.

Fixes: bug #1243749
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit 0c114976eadce0c30ed3961c2d19c56a00fc4cc2)

Change-Id: Ic933b4ef3a91210aa13c9e031e0c61cc1e30ac77

commit_message:
Install Guide: fix ssh command

* Identity file is not mykey, but ~/.ssh/id_rsa (the default).
* CirrOS demands login as user cirros, not user root.

backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit b769913e5a555a3c6b62a21cf4d4e0c5e110b45c)

Change-Id: Ifd37eaa75b3c72204dc7507c4d697af0e954901b

In the previous patch I needed to check for systemd because I was calling "systemctl" specifically.

Here we need to distinguish between the fedora and debian-based package & daemon names. You can run systemd on debian, but you'd still need to call "service apache2 reload" here.

The way it's written, even systemd-enabled debian would still match correctly here, but I thought it'd be a bit more robust this way.

But I've no issue with changing it to a different check if you think it would be better.'}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-10-25 20:28:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
Reload Apache config in one place

Any element depending on apache2 can now just add their config to conf.d
and this will make sure it goes into effect without restarting the
server.

Change-Id: Ic77229d37f833950a3d09d3f72bf0d797750ebd6
Signed-off-by: Tomas Sedovic <tomas@sedovic.cz>

commit_message:
Updates the documentation for nova unit tests

unit_tests.rst is outdated and does not reflect the recent changes
in the run_tests.sh script. Fix required an update of the usage
output of run_tests.sh as well as changes to some references.
Nova now uses testrepository and flake8.

There were also changes to the examples shown in the section
"Running a subset of tests". All the updated examples were tested.

Removes white spaces at the of end 3 lines.

Change-Id: I3fa040d5682ad94d861cef2a64b19b4da947318b
Closes-Bug: #1219040

'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-10-24 09:36:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Ladislav,

This approach works, thanks!

So IIUC the new strategy for group by resource is as follows:

1. retrieve *all* resources
2. exclude any resource without a meter link with rel attribute matching the meter name in question
3. kick off separate threads to query the statistics for each remaining resource
4. inject the statistics into each of these resource objects

Now, I think this multi-step approach could be streamlined by using the new groupby mechanism in the ceilometer API. This would render step #1 unnecessary, and step #3 could be achieved with a single query with the groupby=resource_id query param set.

The statistics in the response would then include a

  'groupby': {'resource_id': RESOURCE_ID}

attribute, which should provide enough information for the per-resource charting to proceed IIUC.

However that alternative approach to fixing the bug would require that groupby support exists in python-ceilometerclient (which doesn't seem to be the case as yet, IIUC). So we would need to add that support on the ceilometer side, release python-ceilometerclient 1.0.7, then update the horizon requirements to bump up the ceiloclient dependency version.

What do you think?

The alternative groupby approach seems to me the right way to go, except that the update of a dependency version would be a concern for backporting to stable/horizon. 

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 7585, 'date': '2013-10-24 11:19:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I would push this patch through, as it could be easily backported, right?

The groupby is planned as optimization. I track most of the Ceilometer optimization work here: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/horizon/+spec/ceilometer-api-enhancements 

I would like to do it as soon as the ceilometerclient is ready. 

What do you think?'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-10-24 15:31:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

@lsmola: yes that's a fair balance between getting it fixed first in an easily backportable way, before resolving in a more optimal manner on master only once the appropriate support in available in the client library. Let's run with that.

Thanks!
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-10-24 15:44:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: No score

Actually one thing that's missing here is a test.

The simplest approach would just be to ensure that in the groupby resource case, the initial resources query is no longer constrained to return only instances, e.g.:

 diff --git a/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/metering/tests.py b/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/metering/tests.py
 index 9bc348b..cd16fe7 100644
 --- a/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/metering/tests.py
 +++ b/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/metering/tests.py
 @@ -316,7 +316,8 @@ class MeteringViewTests(test.APITestCase, test.BaseAdminViewTests):
 
          ceilometerclient = self.stub_ceilometerclient()
          ceilometerclient.resources = self.mox.CreateMockAnything()
 -        ceilometerclient.resources.list(q=IsA(list)).AndReturn(resources)
 +        ceilometerclient.resources.list(q=[]).AndReturn(resources)

Or you could go further, and mock the return of specific resources, some of which have the appropriate meter link with rel='storage.objects' and others not. Then ensure that the parallel statistics queries occur as expected only for a subset of the resources initially returned.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 7585, 'date': '2013-10-25 07:49:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

ok, I am on it'}, {'account_id': 7585, 'date': '2013-10-25 08:17:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7585, 'date': '2013-10-25 08:21:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Ok, adding another resource with different meters should be enough.

You are actually testing in the _verify_series func: self.assertEqual(len(data['series']), len(expected_names))

Adding another resource with different meters shouldn't affect this check, because the resource is filtered out. I guess this should be enough."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-25 09:07:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Broken charting for non compute resources

- Code for resource charts contained query that
  filtered only nova instances. That condition
  is removed. Now it filters resources by the
  meter name.

Fixes bug 1243796

Change-Id: I7debb2b457ede83b726934c082f22307ddc0c630

commit_message:
Pass keywords to the request initialization

The `prepare_request` function accepts keywords corresponding to what
the Request class can take as arguments. This patch passes those kwargs
to the newly created `Request` instance, which is needed for the correct
work of the auth backend.

Partially-Implements blueprint python-marconiclient-v1

Change-Id: Ib333a7ad4d4628e2e5a66ddc91fafc378679f69c

commit_message:
Remove duplicate text from Cinder Troubleshooting

Both section_ts_cinder_config.xml and
section_block_storage_troubleshooting.xml contained the same initial
paragraphs but differences in the rest.

The extra table and text from section_block_storage_troubleshooting.xml has been
moved to section_ts_cinder_config.xml.

section_block_storage_troubleshooting.xml is now obsolete.

Also, fix some typos.

Change-Id: Ife61dbc2bcb9f3a6fa78a8147fee6cfb2e3dfb7f

Jgriffith isnt the driver passed into connector a VolumeDriver? If so then could you please elaborate how it breaks others.

In this change the nfs_mount_point_base for nfs driver need to be passed into RemoteFsClient and there does not seem to be any other way as per current signature of methods to achieve this.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-10-25 13:19:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Navneet,
The problem is that the "driver" that is being used for that init is actually referring to the initiator/connector driver which isn't the same as the "volume driver" that this change passes in.

Actually it's quite confusing and there are some places where I think we could, maybe should clean this up a bit.  

The problem with this patch in terms of "other" driver is that the general iscsi attach to cinder-node functionality breaks.  By passing in the volume-driver object the connector is going to call the driver.get_all_block_devices which actually is part of the connector.host_driver object NOT the volume-driver object.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-10-25 13:33:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Revert "Brick connector fix for NFS drivers"

This reverts commit b6b9df2940ac07f715f759f4c315b2cf088c2320

Passing in driver=self in the base driver connector builder breaks all of the other drivers and isn't the *correct* driver to be passing in.

Simply removing this fixes the functionality, however breaks your tests and I'm not sure of the impact on what you were attempting so I'm reverting.

commit_message:
Add filenames to skip_tracker.py output

This commit adds support for also printing the filenames along with
the bug number in the skip tracker output. This should make it
slightly easier to find the skips and remove them.

Change-Id: Ia3502f1a48bb9e028d046fa60307e398582e6124

commit_message:
Add Missing Newline In OVS Plugin Setup

There is a missing newline between two commands in step 3
of the OVS plugin setup instructions.  This fixes that.

Change-Id: Ic990eb99ae3f5c8159ae16296f73bd472c6bbddf
Fixes: bug #1243734
backport: havana

which missing the time part like "2011-09-05". This behavior is
different than iso8601-0.1.4, so caused glance-{api,registry}'s v1 API
controller provide different result.

This patch fixes this issue via cap iso8601 version to 0.1.4 in
requirement.txt but update test case code since current iso8601-0.1.7

commit_message:
Sync iso8601 requirement and fixes test case failures

1. Sync requirements from global.
2. iso8601>=0.1.7 "parse_date()" could successfully handle date string
which only have date part like YYYY-MM-DD, it caused two Glance test
cases failure.

Fixes bug: 1242501

Change-Id: I2625eb3888111829a9da4d093b34193b8795f264
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Revert "Brick connector fix for NFS drivers"

This reverts commit b6b9df2940ac07f715f759f4c315b2cf088c2320

Passing in driver=self in the base driver connector builder breaks all of the other drivers and isn't the *correct* driver to be passing in.

Simply removing this fixes the functionality, however breaks your tests and I'm not sure of the impact on what you were attempting so I'm reverting.

Change-Id: I0af85a2bc491cc0e23aa6af1f67c2dfed1c7081f

commit_message:
Added some test for image tags

Image-tags are introduced in v2 api
of glance.one can create and delete a
tag for image.

Change-Id: I2ef7e085eb2577232dc0ef08d139341978b007f1

commit_message:
Sync log_handler from Oslo

Resolves an ImportError when enabling publish_errors for
Ceilometer services. Essentially, PublishErrorsHandler was
moved in Oslo from *.log to *.log_handler, but log_handler
was not yet being pulled in.

Oslo commit: Ibf28ba17f81b5ddeda653f6a3501ecac18ffcd42

Change-Id: I23bc7fd0ea4c811e133e743634032fb836c34b22
Fixes: Bug #1244722

commit_message:
put the stackforge library installation behind a conditional

we don't actually want to drag in stackforge libraries all the
time, instead ensure that we have enabled stackforge_libs before
doing it.

Change-Id: Ic1c2e3d19e106a2aa0db9725d16a8b207546c23d

LGTM, but I'm not sure what the impact on the API will be when these exceptions are reraised, instead of converted."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2013-10-25 10:17:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Yea, it will return 500 (internal server error) http code and the exception message, which seems alright.'}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2013-10-25 11:20:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Lucas, maybe to send internal db errors to client not very good, what you think about

except Exception as e:
    LOG.exception(e)
    raise exception.IronicException('DB error...') #return 500"}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2013-10-25 12:58:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So, I tend to agree with u here that we might just want to LOG the error and return a generic message like "Internal Error".

But I could argue on the other side as well since our user are cloud admins returning the error directly might help then to identify the problem more quick and as they r admins they cloud then to take some action to fix the problem (different from normal end users).

Now, if they can access the db and fix the problem they probably have access to the logs as well, so I would just log something more generic and tell them to go and check the logs for a more detailed message.

tl;dr: IMO return a more generic error and LOG the error message :)

Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2013-10-25 13:22:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Lucas, agree, but only for a time while Ironic does not have rock-solid production quality :)'}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2013-10-25 13:25:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2013-10-25 16:58:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

A few comments on the discussion

- we can't assume a user of Ironic has DB or LOG file access.

- the exceptions returned from ironic-api may bubble all the way up to Nova, and be returned to nova's clients too!

- "Internal error" is never the right thing to tell a client. OTOH, we should never return a stack trace from the API, either.

There's a middle ground somewhere, and I think that raising the real error here is fine, as long as the middleware/parsable_error.py handler is doing its job (which, afaict, it is NOT, but that's a separate issue).'}, {'account_id': 5805, 'date': '2013-10-25 18:38:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

commit_message:
Fix exceptions handling in controllers

1. DB api create_* methods not raises IronicException.
2. Non-Ironic exception from DB api create_* method
should cause server error.

Also unnecessary wsme.validate decorator removed from
chassis controller.

Change-Id: I71279f7db5c93804aeac077c034e09cb907b1fb9

Seems like you are jamming a lot of changes into one with this. Just reading the commit message indicates there are at least 3."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-10-15 19:57:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Another comment for the checksum validation, if part of that is to help make sure images are cleaned up, it's not happening.  This is a dump from our test system that we run tempest against for havana with the powervm driver, you'll see that the images are piling up on the system even though the backing instances are deleted from nova:

http://ocdc.hursley.ibm.com/pastebin/d193cd39a"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-10-15 19:57:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

A publicly accessible paste is probably helpful:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/48516/'}, {'account_id': 6722, 'date': '2013-10-16 01:21:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Matt,

The MD5 check existed there before I started working on this.
I guess that's just integrity check.

We did meet the case , transfer failure left image files with size 0 due to full of disk. We need clean up the image file with size 0. 

For your case , I think we need something like other hypervisor did to manage cached images , such as https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/virt/libvirt/imagecache.py"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-10-16 01:54:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

ChangBo, yeah, I think the answer is to implement the manage_image_cache method for the powervm driver which will do the cleanup for us.  If the FTP transfer fails then we should get an exception from that, we shouldn't have to do checksum validation on every image transfer.  I'll plan on working on manage_image_cache for Icehouse so we can remove this checksum validation."}, {'account_id': 6722, 'date': '2013-10-16 02:01:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Matt, one case we need consider, if we don't clean up the image everytime when ftp transfer fails, then Admin release some space of disk to make sure there is enough space to use.
We'll fail to boot , because the wrong image existing will skip the ftp transfer according to current logic."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-10-16 03:20:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

ChangBo, cleaning up incomplete corrupted images is one thing, we know the path to the bad image in that case so I don't see why the checksum validation would be needed in that scenario - if we catch the ftp failure exception from ftplib, we should know the remote path to the file and be able to delete it, right?"}, {'account_id': 7040, 'date': '2013-10-16 03:41:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(7 inline comments)

"}, {'account_id': 5313, 'date': '2013-10-18 19:16:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Matt Riedemann: Any file transfer has the potential of messing up the integrity of the file. The transport protocol, on this case ftp, will not be able to catch some potential issues, this is specially the case when the file is big. Keeping the checksum in place is a matter of integrity. Can you make sure the image here is the same as over there? The only way to know for sure is by comparing checksums'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-10-18 19:39:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Say what now? FTP over TCP with a clean exit should always produce a sane file. You fetched the image from glance with HTTP over TCP but didn't verify it... What's the difference?"}, {'account_id': 5313, 'date': '2013-10-18 20:23:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (9 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 5313, 'date': '2013-10-18 20:24:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 5313, 'date': '2013-10-18 20:33:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Dan yes, TCP protects about data packet transfer issues. But I don't see how there is guarantee the file on the remote file system is not corrupted without a check sum. FTP, as far as I understand does not take check sums. Like I said, I'm not saying removing will be the end of the world but I can say the extra check is worth it if performance hit is min. On glance, I think glance keeps the check sum stored as metadata props, so checkin will be an extra protection. I always thought the glance client will take care of making sure, but could be wrong."}, {'account_id': 5313, 'date': '2013-10-18 20:35:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Matt Odden: The extra changes for eventlet and md5sum rename was part of good feedback from reviewers not sure I want to drop that know'}, {'account_id': 5371, 'date': '2013-10-18 20:37:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-10-18 20:41:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

FTP does not do checksums, that's correct. There's no need. If you have a file that is cut up into blocks and each block is transferred in order and checksum'd individually, then the file can be assumed to be whole.

Again, you fetched it from glance with no verification. It was uploaded to glance in the first place with no verification. Your browser downloaded the HTML and JSON you're reading this from with no verification. If this wasn't a pretty safe thing to rely on, a lot of things would be broken all the time :)

This is, of course, barring any bugs in your disk driver, network driver, network stack, etc. However, again, lots of stuff would be broken if that didn't work, and it'd be corrupting your reading of the remotely-computed checksum anyway :)"}, {'account_id': 5313, 'date': '2013-10-18 20:47:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-18 21:00:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Doesn't seem to work

I noticed tempest failed, I think you hit bug(s): https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/1226337'}, {'account_id': 5313, 'date': '2013-10-18 21:08:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Glance does check checksum on upload there is an optional header you can pass that will check, like I said not sure if glance download takes care of that too, I would have to check. Also the fact that you transfer all packets at the TCP network level does not mean the bits on the file are intact... hardware issues can cause that. Of course that hardware issues are not common. So sure not issue must of the time, but when it happens it brakes, it is small risk but a risk nonetheless. Having matching checksum gives you an extra potection that may or may not be needed. I just don't see why we should remove robustness from code unless there are considerable impact on performance. Maybe we should ask mriedem why he brought it up to begin with. I don't think is the end of the world to remove either way but will prefer for him to pitch in first if that is OK"}, {'account_id': 5313, 'date': '2013-10-18 21:16:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

commit_message:
Refactoring powervm blockdev for configdrive usage

Refactored blockdev module to reuse copy_image_file functionality
regardless of implementation being Local Adapter now or something
else in the future. Moving copy_image_file and its dependencies
to base class. Renamed local md5sum functions to match name of
remote md5sum function. Also, changed time.sleep to eventlet.sleep
call to make it explicit that it is yielding on green threads and
avoid depending on monkey patch of time module.

Implements bp powervm-configdrive

Change-Id: I333b0cf3660d747b744b431d4547fb066f9ad451

commit_message:
Enable gettext alias for all ironicclient modules

In order to support i18n, each string has to be wrapped in gettext.
To simplify the coding, an alias _(msg) is defined in gettextutils
for the gettext function. This patch adds the gettext domain so
that all the code under ironiclient can use it without explicitly
importing it.

Change-Id: Idab14125c7eb8ad5f3a00b40e0bccf1a5ff9e228

commit_message:
Add ceph_config ini helper

* add a ini_file helper as ceph_config.
* set the seperator as ' = ' in order to be the same as ceph-deploy
* add path param so that seperator can be easily tested.
** also allows for users to change the default path if desired.
* add test case to prove spacing around seperator.
* add simple test case to ensure type works.

Closes-bug: #1243852
Change-Id: I0f3bb41d75d48d8af3b5b7cfb7768c4d3de2c002

commit_message:
Instance delete should check for 'DELETED' status

Currently in Instance.py check_delete_complete method is waiting
for 'NotFound' exception. This change is to wait for 'DELETED'
state to speed up the resource/stack delete.

Closes-Bug: #1243389

Change-Id: I09712f548f40bb13c2b322550007f5bd30dfb3e2

commit_message:
Provide service type management code structure

Reasons for refactoring:
- current code structure is orientied on mysql management implementation;
- there is no chanse to make new service types management
code fittable in current package/module structure;
- backuping process implementation is mysql/percona-orientied,
it should be renamed and should be configurable due to service type;
- "query" is abstract word for querying into database,
current query.py implementation is SQL orientied - it should be renamed;

Updates:
1.Providing new package hierarchy:
   guestagent/manager/service_type/service.py
   guestagent/manager/service_type/manager.py
   guestagent/manager/service_type/system.py
2.Renaming strategy implementations per each service_type
   guestagent/strategies/backup/mysql_impl.py
3.Externalizing operating system definer form system.py
 which used in pkg.py
4.Renaming query to sql_query.

Implement: blueprint refactor-ga-for-other-engines-support
Change-Id: I5fa5f037056bedf5464e99720cbe03b877c27fba

commit_message:
Add Fedora support for Apache 2

The diskimage-builder's fedora element now (as of 1c132f6a) contains the
necessary package mappings, making apache2 compatible with fedora.

Change-Id: I3a66e1791502aba9f2e603544ac0bed6be9ba024
Signed-off-by: Tomas Sedovic <tomas@sedovic.cz>

'}, {'account_id': 8304, 'date': '2013-10-21 15:39:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

In this patch, I have modified the node processes that are available from the HDP plugin.  This was done to simplify things for the user when we can determine where certain node processes need to be deployed implicitly.  An example of this is AMBAR_AGENT, which needs to be present in every node group.

As a result, the integration tests are breaking because the test node templates that are being used contain the recently removed node processes(AMBARI_AGENT, NAGIOS_MONITOR).  This causes a failure in checks in the controller.  This can be fixed by creating new node groups without these node processes.

But, to me it seems wrong the the savanna controller is doing this validation.  That is what the validate() SPI call on the plugin is for.  I think that it would be better to simply let the plugin do the validation instead of the controller trying to guess what is valid.'}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2013-10-21 17:48:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Allow generate_sample MODULEPATH to be set in env

This commit allows the default modulepath to optionally be set with
an environmental variable. This is useful for tempest because config
isn't used in the same way because tempest is executed in a test
runner. So to enable using generator.py it has to be wrapped to
manually load the config before calling generate(). This will enable
specifying the local tempest generator wrapper module without modifying
the oslo synced script.

Change-Id: Iacef39d6ae7693ecd09b113401b7db52afc53d17

commit_message:
NetApp fix ssc volume filtering inconsistency

This fixes the situation when the actual netapp
volume data structure becomes inconsistent
because of operating on the actual object
than the copy of it. It also introduces some checks
before calculating volume stats.

Change-Id: I626f9ca9aa8c7cc41ba4aa6058f14cc040f7301f
Closes-Bug:#1243081

NetApp fix for compression and dedup stats

This change fixes the incorrect stats reported
for compression and deduplication by NetApp
iscsi and nfs backend.

Change-Id: I3e97d953b3ea2231c3eb1f950b0ca6705b3b2286
Closes-Bug:#1236839

commit_message:
Adds tests for user extra attribute behavior

Extra attributes (not directly defined on the model) are stashed away
in a JSON blob.  When returning a user entity they are pulled from the
blob and added directly to the entity.

Change-Id: Ic85b692dda2530efa2ef9833a8a8eed0b12bc7fb
Related-Bug: #1214686

actual use.

commit_message:
Move CA key from certs directory to private directory

Unlike certs which are public keys are private. The CA key file was
improperly located in the certs directory with the public certs. It's
vital to protect the CA key, it's one of the most security sensitive
files in the system. We already had a private directory for keys,
/etc/keystone/ssl/private where the signing key is located. This fix
moves the CA key into /etc/keystone/ssl/private from
/etc/keystone/ssl/certs.

We also update all relevant files to note the change. During so it was
observered etc/keystone.conf.sample used the wrong parent directory
/etc/keystone/pki, the directory /etc/keystone/ssl is the directory in
actual use.

Fixes: bug #1206254

Change-Id: I014e9f79093a6aa59cd5b3bb6cefa4c6dced67a6

commit_message:
Port server actions unittests to V3 API Part 2

Ports the server actions unittests to test the V3 API.
This mostly involved CamelCase to camel_case changes
and adpating the URLs to point to the V3 API instead of
the V2 API.

It also includes
- Fixing a bug in the admin_password extension picked up by
  the tests where bad request data is not always handled properly
- Generate image ref urls that point to glance api rather than
  the nova api. This fits in with the decision to not port the images
  extension to the V3 API which is implemented here:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40565/
- Moves admin password related tests to the admin password unittests
  test file as this functionality has been moved out from core.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-unittests

Change-Id: I58b4c0103c824898183fca890c74c3c1cbe19633

Add dracut-network to fedora undercloud nodes

This is no longer a dependency of the fedora element but is still needed
on undercloud nodes so explicitly needs to be pulled in.

commit_message:
add lib/stackforge to let us test wsme / pecan from git

wsme and pecan libraries have migrated to stackforge for
development. If we support them in devstack, we can use their git
version instead of the release version, which ensures that they
won't break the rest of OpenStack when they cut a new release.

This is similar to how oslo testing works. Long term we probably
want a more generic mechanism to handle this, but for now, this
should get us rolling, and get them gating.

Change-Id: Icf3475f433081c7c625864107d7e118e214396e1

commit_message:
GlusterFS: set correct filename when cloning volume

When cloning a volume, the volume[name] field was populated
with incorrect data, resulting in an unexpected filename containing
the volume data.  This results in failures of later operations on
that cloned volume.

Change-Id: I067ed44cebdc8e91e9ded326953fd0c99d003f05
Closes-Bug: #1244238

commit_message:
Conductors maintan driver list in the DB

To facilitate exposing a list of drivers in the API,
and keep track of which ironic-conductor instance status,
this patch ...
* adds a new 'conductors' table in the DB
* adds a Conductor object class (with intentionally limited
  functionality)
* adds db/api methods for register/unregister/get/touch
* adds periodic task to conductor to maintain its updated_at field
* adds an additional db/api method to retrieve a list of drivers
  which are registered by active conductor instances

Change-Id: I1ebdb92d5c2d6ad1a6d1717dd13ff51be181ccc0

commit_message:
Adjust to non-deprecated names in Keyring 1.6.+

Keyring 1.1 moved the concrete backend implementations into their
own modules. As we depend on 1.6.1+, we can make use of the new
name and remove the old one without deprecation-fallback.

commit_message:
Remove DHCP_DRIVER option

We can safely remove DHCP_DRIVER option and use
neutron-dhcp-agent directly instead, as it's the
only supported dhcp driver now.

Change-Id: Ibb13f0eb81b3faf570891ca8c7e742f52b7a5dfc

commit_message:
Supports paginate query for two get nodes DB APIs

In DB APIs that return a list of nodes, limiting and sorting the
output is necessary for a large number of output nodes. This is
especially important for the GUI that uses the APIs where the view
is limited. This patch adds limit, marker, sort_key and sort_dir
to get_associated_nodes and get_unassociated_nodes DB APIs.

Change-Id: Ia2c616fff65a03bace1244fe646bdf0cf5f30a29

commit_message:
Replace basestring by six for python3 compatability

The builtin basestring abstract type was removed in python3,
use str instead, we need to using six.string_types to replace
the basestring for py3 compatibility.

Partial Implements bp: basestring-py3-compatible

Change-Id: Ifb3d02a18b78f97e7981b73ab06a989d7bc69685

commit_message:
change assertEquals to assertEqual

According to http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html
assertEquals is a deprecated alias of assertEqual.

Change-Id: Ia81546aea72d42a70c68280f6d97c41fdf0d7a29

commit_message:
add some tests for host and seperate negative ones

For host operation, there are some APIs: list, show, update, startup,
shutdown, reboot. This patch will mainly add some negative tests for
update, startup, shutdown, reboot. It is important to note that, for
Libvirt Driver currently, there are no implementations for
set_host_enabled/host_maintenance_mode/host_power_action.

Change-Id: Ia810b956a20eae67e8ec43e3edf9fcb019f71711

[{'created': '2013-10-23 06:36:50.000000000', 'message': "Properly handle transport URL config on the client

On the client side, in the rabbit and qpid drivers, we use a connection
pool to avoid opening a connection for each message we send. However,
there is only currently one connection pool per process:

 def get_connection_pool(conf, connection_cls):
     with _pool_create_sem:
         # Make sure only one thread tries to create the connection pool.
         if not connection_cls.pool:
             connection_cls.pool = ConnectionPool(conf, connection_cls)
     return connection_cls.pool

This is a nasty artifact of the original RPC having no conectp of a
transport context - everything was a global. We'll fix this soon enough.

In the meantime, we need to make sure we only use this connection pool
where we're not using the default transport configuration from the
config file - i.e. where we supply a transport URL.

The use case here is cells - we send messages to a remote cell by
connecting to it using a transport URL. In our devstack testing, the
two cells are on the same Rabbit broker but under different virtual
hosts. Because we were always using the connection pool on the client
side, we were seeing both cells always send messages to the '/' virtual
host.

Note - avoiding the connection pool in the case of cells is the same
behaviour as the current RPC code:

 def cast_to_server(conf, context, server_params, topic, msg, connection_pool):
     ...
     with ConnectionContext(conf, connection_pool, pooled=False,
                            server_params=server_params) as conn:

Change-Id: I2f35b45ef237bb85ab8faf58a408c03fcb1de9d7

commit_message:
Properly handle transport URL config on the client

On the client side, in the rabbit and qpid drivers, we use a connection
pool to avoid opening a connection for each message we send. However,
there is only currently one connection pool per process:

 def get_connection_pool(conf, connection_cls):
     with _pool_create_sem:
         # Make sure only one thread tries to create the connection pool.
         if not connection_cls.pool:
             connection_cls.pool = ConnectionPool(conf, connection_cls)
     return connection_cls.pool

This is a nasty artifact of the original RPC having no conectp of a
transport context - everything was a global. We'll fix this soon enough.

In the meantime, we need to make sure we only use this connection pool
where we're not using the default transport configuration from the
config file - i.e. where we supply a transport URL.

The use case here is cells - we send messages to a remote cell by
connecting to it using a transport URL. In our devstack testing, the
two cells are on the same Rabbit broker but under different virtual
hosts. Because we were always using the connection pool on the client
side, we were seeing both cells always send messages to the '/' virtual
host.

Note - avoiding the connection pool in the case of cells is the same
behaviour as the current RPC code:

 def cast_to_server(conf, context, server_params, topic, msg, connection_pool):
     ...
     with ConnectionContext(conf, connection_pool, pooled=False,
                            server_params=server_params) as conn:

Change-Id: I2f35b45ef237bb85ab8faf58a408c03fcb1de9d7

commit_message:
Solve lint issues, add basic documentation, and minors improvments

  [lint issues]
  * class not documented
  * variable not enclosed in {}
  * double quoted string containing no variables
  * case statement without a default case
  * indentation of => is not properly aligned
  * soft and hard tabs

  [improvments]
  * Use a case instead of a if/if

Change-Id: I39293ed0636f4226317602eda4b0b121a4f9a9a3

commit_message:
Mock out os.path.isdir for brick connector test

1766a5a "Check if dir exists..." introduced a new call
to os.path.isdir() but did not mock it out, so tests will fail
on systems where that directory is not present.

Related-Bug: #1243980
Closes-Bug: #1244418

Change-Id: I4a3bfee30992931478e9bf59bbea229daf8fbca9

Benchmark test to boot server and bounce it N times

Implements a benchmark test which will boot a server and then "bounce"
it with specified operations: stop/start, soft reboot and hard
reboot.

[{'created': '2013-10-17 22:51:18.000000000', 'message': "compute: virt: Fix Instance creation

Instance is a namedtuple defined in ceilometer/compute/virt/inspector.py. Its
fields are 'name' and 'UUID'. Therefore, the 'uuid' field used in
inspect_instances should be 'UUID'.

commit_message:
compute: virt: Fix Instance creation

Instance is a namedtuple defined in ceilometer/compute/virt/inspector.py. Its
fields are 'name' and 'UUID'. Therefore, the 'uuid' field used in
inspect_instances should be 'UUID'.

Change-Id: I844b457bc75603d6325bfe3eb239012cec12c6b9

commit_message:
Support defining update_allowed in the property_schema

This has a couple of advantages:
- docs will be easier to generate
- everything property related is in one place
- it's a bit easier dealing with TemplateResources
- it will allow us to set update_allowed on nested schema

Change-Id: I5e59bc07e51fe4c5d58871cb2adcef7e16f9b2af
Partial-bug: #1240583

commit_message:
Stub out unmocked keystone in test_engine_service

Keystone needs to be mocked out whenever stacks may do something that
triggers authentication. In this case failures to auth would not result
in a failure of the test because we are not asserting the end state of
the stack or the list of events we expect.

Change-Id: I401971cfc984bd71c611eae70aeb33b2f5a3c8c6
Closes-Bug: #1227962

Remove mapping of atftpd to tftpd-server

These are different tftp implementations, tftpd-hpa and tftpd-server are
equivalent, this mapping was added in a previous commit.

commit_message:
Add redhat mapping from tftpd-hpa to tftp-server

This will be needed by a patch I'll be submitting to t-e-i to
change the tftp implementation used by ubuntu, so that both
Ubuntu and Fedora can use the same implementation.

Change-Id: Ie9581265dfa2c37342e01162fe580b1948dd3e03

commit_message:
Add the doc build tools

tools/build_docs.sh generates the devstack.org website from the static
pages and generated pages created by running shocco against a DevStack
checkout.

Note that while this is the complete auto page generation of the
devstack.org site, pushing the content back to GitHub is limited
to those with push access to the current repo.

Partial-bug 1235626

Change-Id: I61dc3d56e4a4832a9ddd1904dd8af65c15a17e50

[{'created': '2013-10-24 20:53:53.000000000', 'message': 'Tolerate lookup failures in Fn::Select

A wait condition will return an empty dict for its Data attribute
until it has been created, however Fn::Select on Data will be evaluated
before the wait condition is created (for example, during stack-list
or stack-show). The current error raising of Fn::Select leads these
operations to fail.

This change results in Fn::Select evaluation behaving in the
following way:
- KeyError on dict lookup failure results in empty string
- IndexError on list index results in empty string
- Passing an empty string as the value results in an empty string

Closes-Bug: #1243958
Change-Id: I3b01c8ce5dc56e804016274282d2ee69f539bf40
'}]
commit_message:
Tolerate lookup failures in Fn::Select

A wait condition will return an empty dict for its Data attribute
until it has been created, however Fn::Select on Data will be evaluated
before the wait condition is created (for example, during stack-list
or stack-show). The current error raising of Fn::Select leads these
operations to fail.

This change results in Fn::Select evaluation behaving in the
following way:
- KeyError on dict lookup failure results in empty string
- IndexError on list index results in empty string
- Passing an empty string as the value results in an empty string

Closes-Bug: #1243958
Change-Id: I3b01c8ce5dc56e804016274282d2ee69f539bf40

commit_message:
Enable keystone authentication in Ironic

Currently Ironic installation script leaves authenticaiton
strategy in its default value which is noauth. This is not
relevant for the most of development and testing environments.

This patch sets authentication strategy for Ironic to keystone
and specifies the path to the policy file.

Closes-bug: #1233612
Change-Id: Idacbda05663e7ef949cbce0dbdf28eaa36b6a1a9

commit_message:
Fix cacert argument to HTTPS connection

This fixes a typo that broke the client for HTTPS URLs.

Added a basic test to cover this case.
Coverage is very low in common/http.py.

Change-Id: Ic440f20f463c3b8558a7639f1015096a01496cf8
Closes-bug: 1244091

Fix bad classname

During change Ie8e0d17a95e8378733dd21ab341dfad1331edf6e it seems, that

commit_message:
Add offline support to devtest.sh

We can now re-use images/sources from a previous run. On a sample test
machine this cuts total runtime of the script from around 1 hour to
around 20 minutes.

Change-Id: I4643b24e624f725836427b580713c0fb68ca1da2

commit_message:
Remove dependency on dracut-network

Now that we have moved onto neutron-dhcp-agent. dracut-network is no
longer needed, infact it was getting in the way. Dracut wasn't
requesting the classless-static-routes dhcp parameter but was
configuring networking. Removing this causes the network service to
redo dhcp and set the appropriate static route (specifically so
overcloud nodes are routed to the correct metadata server). This element
is still required for undercloud nodes so needs to be included there.

Change-Id: Ic23560164aff7791dd87ed2c3ad008efd248ae93

Thanks (very very much) for the heads up and the attachment to this review. I agree this doesn't belong in Nova and although it affects our build/deploy system it should be a quick fix. 

Looks good. Thanks again!"}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-10-09 19:55:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I'm in two minds about this one.

The XenAPI plugins are consumed in dom0 and therefore need some form of packaging to get them from wherever nova is, and unlike Nova itself it's pretty much guaranteed that dom0 is RPM based rather than deb or another form of packaging.

On the other hand, as we move towards xenserver-core as an option we can be on top of debian and the plugins might need to be put in different directories to satisfy the directory structures...

I think in a nutshell I think I'm happy for them to be removed, but I would like a viewpoint from Euan Harris who has been working on packaging in Citrix recently.  I'm sure Euan will comment tomorrow."}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-10-09 19:57:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Actually should have been -1 until Euan has a chance to reply - if he's happy then I am!"}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2013-10-09 20:03:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2013-10-09 20:11:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: No score

Eh.  I guess I'm not sure how I feel about this.

The plugins are plugins that install into XenServer dom0 and cannot be installed by the top level setup.py

I almost feel like there should be a nice way to package them up included in the source tree."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-10-09 20:18:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Joe, so how about stuff like this?

I've discussed with Euan and Mate and we're all happy for it to be removed from Nova.

We'll maintain an RPM outside of Nova for the RPM that we're building for Dom0."}, {'account_id': 7952, 'date': '2013-10-10 09:47:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Ok.   We already have a plugins spec file in xenserver-core; we can adapt it for XenServer proper.'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-10-10 16:16:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hmmm. So we discussed this a long time ago and it was decided that since there is only one XenServer distro it was Okay for the SPEC files to live in the tree. This is only to build the plugin RPM... so it seems reasonable for them to live together since there is a 1-1 relationship.

I see no harm in them living here... there is a very low level of maintenance/turnover."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-10-10 17:36:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Dan, I think its time to revisit that decision. I don't think keeping this in causes much harm, its more about does it belong at all, and should nova-core be responsible for maintaining / understanding / reviewing it.

See Bob Balls comment "On the other hand, as we move towards xenserver-core as an option we can be on top of debian and the plugins might need to be put in different directories to satisfy the directory structures..."

Also if we keep this in I would like to see some gating on this to make sure we don't ship broken code.'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-10-10 17:46:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm still OK with this change - but I think we need to move the plugin files out of etc/xapi.d/plugins and just put them in this directory?"}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-10-10 17:48:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I should have said the reason I was suggesting that is because otherwise it seems to only be partially removing the RPM "stuff".

On the other hand, that would break devstack so a corresponding change would be needed there too.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-10-10 19:04:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: No score

I didn't think about the 1-1 relationship point that Dan Prince brought up.  Chris Behrens mentioned that on IRC, as well.  I think that's a decent argument for just leaving it alone if it's convenient for folks.  I'm neutral on this now."}, {'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2013-10-10 19:08:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Neutral on this as well TBH'}, {'account_id': 5044, 'date': '2013-10-10 21:52:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

FYI: this change might have triggered this discussion: 

https://review.openstack.org/49580

We just started to use this spec file on a daily basis.

I don't care where does it live, but we need this functionality. It was convenient to have it here, but I understand why you want get rid of it. I am not sure about the benefit of the removal, but if we can't change it, let's remove it."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-10-10 21:59:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Bob, depending on what the consensus is, I will make your requested change in the next revision.

This is part of a bigger story for me, which is the entire plugins directory.  Which as far as I know is only xenapi code, so a generic 'plugins' directory is misleading.  And I don't know of any gating tests on it. And if code isn't tested I assume its broken.

I am fine with leaving this in if we can gate on it somehow, or at least something like smokestack.  Does smokestack use this?  I assume not because if so this patch would have broken it."}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-10-11 06:46:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

SmokeStack doesn't use the RPM, but it does depend on the directory structure.  Therefore changing the directory structure to remove the RPMness will break smokestack.

Citrix's internal CI depends on both of them - as well as the devstack usage of the plugin directory.
We build the RPM from the nova sources and include it in a package to distribute.
The current change, of course, breaks our internal CI but if the consensus is that the SPEC file shouldn't live here then we'll store it somewhere else and update our CI / build system to get it from elsewhere."}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-10-11 06:48:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

p.s. We are, of course, looking at options for how we could publish the results from our CI generically.

If the decision is to keep this SPEC file in then we can make sure that either it's used by smokestack (which it probably should be!) or our internal results are published."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-10-14 13:34:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Its a tricky one.

There are now multiple XenServer distros, so there is less argument for this to live here.

It gets used by devstack, prehaps its better living in there? Then we can gate properly (on at least some parts) of that devstack code.'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-10-14 13:37:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

If there are multiple distros targeted here I think we should probably let this go then.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-10-15 18:59:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-10-15 19:02:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Why are you moving the plugin files (in the same commit)?

This will almost certainly break things..."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-10-15 19:13:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I'm not fussed either way - but I am surprised that smokestack passed...

I think this is a bug in smokestack because it just copies the files over.  In this case there were no files to copy over:
> rake aborted!
> Failed to install plugins.

SmokeStack should have failed the test at that point, rather than continuing to run Torpedo tests.

The torpedo tests passed because the plugins from the previous run were still present on the hypervisor.

I did, however, expect the unit test failure as one of the tests depends on the plugins file to extract the version of the plugins - and if the file location moves it wouldn't be able to find it."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-10-15 21:39:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-10-15 21:39:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Remove xenapi rpm building code

Nova shouldn't be building any types of packages. And if we are we should
be testing this code in gate somewhere.

Change-Id: I70d82a6173b5eda183d4e49d330ae97dd14f9078

commit_message:
Nova db/api.py docstring cleanups...

We no longer use LazyPluggable for the db_backend, and
dbapi_use_tpool options. These now come from
nova.openstack.common.db.api.

Also, removed doc about enable_new_services which seemed a bit
lonely without the rest and probably isn't needed since the
config option help explains it well enough.

Change-Id: I14d00e013a1a0c0dfc80e0bba8ad82e97940d6ac

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-24 14:13:29.000000000', 'message': 'Fix processing of routes in init-neutron-ovs

The existing routes via the external network interface
are parsed incorrectly, which makes init-neutron-ovs
fail and leaves the external bridge in partially configured
state. This means that the network node is unreachable
over the external network.

Closes-Bug: #1244188

Change-Id: Ifae4f24c7c08db0ab0f1885db604152ffa1d1a12
'}, {'created': '2013-10-25 06:44:04.000000000', 'message': 'Fix processing of routes in init-neutron-ovs

The existing routes via the external network interface
are parsed incorrectly (routes are not splitted on new
lines), which makes init-neutron-ovs fail and leaves the
external bridge in partially configured state.

Closes-Bug: #1244188

Change-Id: Ifae4f24c7c08db0ab0f1885db604152ffa1d1a12
'}, {'created': '2013-10-25 06:46:24.000000000', 'message': 'Fix processing of routes in init-neutron-ovs

The existing routes via the external network interface
are parsed incorrectly (routes are not split on new
lines), which makes init-neutron-ovs fail and leaves the
external bridge in partially configured state.

Closes-Bug: #1244188

Change-Id: Ifae4f24c7c08db0ab0f1885db604152ffa1d1a12
'}]
commit_message:
Fix processing of routes in init-neutron-ovs

The existing routes via the external network interface
are parsed incorrectly (routes are not split on new
lines), which makes init-neutron-ovs fail and leaves the
external bridge in partially configured state.

Closes-Bug: #1244188

Change-Id: Ifae4f24c7c08db0ab0f1885db604152ffa1d1a12

commit_message:
Install Guide: Attempt to fix heat install

Heat install does not currently work.

This patch takes steps towards fixing it.

Use connection instead of sql_connection also for Ubuntu.
Markup fixes

Backport: stable/havana
Closes-Bug: 1240396

Change-Id: I1d2ce9553667f6c3dace517c0f33219d35df9bc4

[{'created': '2013-10-17 02:09:09.000000000', 'message': 'Allows delete on router gateway interface

Currently user could clear the gateway set on a router but
couldn't delete the same gateway interface form the router
details page.

Code was checking if the owner was router gateway
--datum['device_owner'] == 'network:router_gateway'
and  returning false.  Fix is to change it to return true
which allows gateway interface to be deleted.

Dont know what was the original intention was but if it was
to not allow gateway interface to be deleted from router details page
then we could alternatively disable the delete interface button for
gateway interface on router detail page(other interfaces will
still have the delete button)  and that leaves the only way
to delete gateway interface, is to go the router list page and
click on "clear gateway" button.

I think allowing the user to delete the gateway interface also from
the router detail page will be consistent behavior.

Change-Id: I688491cd344689f5d0972e4de5b0cd594ed83de8
'}]
commit_message:
Allows delete on router gateway interface

Currently user could clear the gateway set on a router but
couldn't delete the same gateway interface form the router
details page.

Code was checking if the owner was router gateway
--datum['device_owner'] == 'network:router_gateway'
and  returning false.  Fix is to change it to return true
which allows gateway interface to be deleted.

Dont know what was the original intention was but if it was
to not allow gateway interface to be deleted from router details page
then we could alternatively disable the delete interface button for
gateway interface on router detail page(other interfaces will
still have the delete button)  and that leaves the only way
to delete gateway interface, is to go the router list page and
click on "clear gateway" button.

I think allowing the user to delete the gateway interface also from
the router detail page will be consistent behavior.

Change-Id: I688491cd344689f5d0972e4de5b0cd594ed83de8

commit_message:
Fedora 18+ and EL 7+ feature more granular libvirt packaging

Fedora 18 or later and RHEL (or derivatives) 7 or later feature a
more granular libvirt packaging, thereby allowing to install only
just the necessary packages.

Most notably, this way no default libvirt network is set up. In the
past, the existence of an interface virbr0 with an IPv4 address of
192.168.122.1/24 often caused confusion with users when debugging
network issues.

Change-Id: I6d5721f59b39bde86fc863f8d5bbfcbf2fb2a4e3

[{'created': '2013-10-16 21:41:29.000000000', 'message': "Add Config Options for Block Device Creation Timeout

Upon creating a new block device, we await the device's creation,
polling every 1 second 60 times to see if the device has been created.
We want to be able to configure the polling interval and number of times
to poll before failing, since different environments could have different
time constraints.

Two configuration options have been added:
* poll_blk_dev_tries defines the maximum number of attempts before failing
* poll_blk_dev_interval defines the number of seconds between attempts

The defaults for these options are the old hard-coded values (60 and 1,
respectively).

Change-Id: I7c9168bfc36a03a2e0a3c46dddae0109865398dc
Fixes: bug #1213953
"}]
commit_message:
Add Config Options for Block Device Creation Timeout

Upon creating a new block device, we await the device's creation,
polling every 1 second 60 times to see if the device has been created.
We want to be able to configure the polling interval and number of times
to poll before failing, since different environments could have different
time constraints.

Two configuration options have been added:
* poll_blk_dev_tries defines the maximum number of attempts before failing
* poll_blk_dev_interval defines the number of seconds between attempts

The defaults for these options are the old hard-coded values (60 and 1,
respectively).

Change-Id: I7c9168bfc36a03a2e0a3c46dddae0109865398dc
Fixes: bug #1213953

commit_message:
Fixes datastore selection bug

Currently the vmwareapi drivers will only select the first
available datastore it finds, even when there are other
datastores with capacity, it will fill one datastore completely
and then die.

Closes-bug: 1227825

Change-Id: I24f85114ea3f014950c27c0c91a6be352990d263
(cherry picked from commit 6c4b89a2ad51f92707acc01908b63bc507ad8fe7)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/test_vmwareapi_vm_util.py
	nova/virt/vmwareapi/vm_util.py

Change-Id: I6e653a9bc39580164981e066345dd214229f7ff7

commit_message:
Sync requirements with OpenStack/requirements

This is the result of a update.py run from OpenStack/requirements,
which fixes the requirements to proper capitalisation, removes
the dependency on d2to1 and raises the version requirements
to be exactly in sync with the requirements of other modules.

Fixes-Bug: #1232235

Change-Id: I67e85302e80b9c1af4ec50ad006517586da1e441

commit_message:
Strip VLAN tag from tunnel payload

This is a grizzly-specific patch to strip the VLAN tag from GRE tunnel
payloads. This has already been accomplished in havana by
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/41239/, but that patch cannot be
cherry picked for grizzly due to extensive unrelated changes.

Note that the resubmit action is used in place of the normal action to
avoid flooding all tunnels with unicast traffic.

Closes-Bug: 1224244
Change-Id: I1dd5e61eb36ebe2c73dbfbc7be2cd3b6c4c2f427

commit_message:
Limit instance fault messages to 255 characters

The instance_fault.message column is a VARCHAR(255).  By default,
MySQL silently truncates entries that are too long.  PostgreSQL
throws an error instead.  So we need to truncate the message field
before we try inserting into that column, to avoid errors from
very long messages in PostgreSQL (or MySQL configured to not allow
this).

Fixes bug #1217167

(cherry picked from commit 21ec8a13be131c700023e97f8f55b34340dd73e8)

Conflicts:
	nova/compute/utils.py

Change-Id: Ia959d64a8bc162a33ba818f1006e9779207b4796

The newer libguestfs as it used by nova not compatible with the
hard link protection.

This option is disabled on most systems, but it is enabled on f19 by
default.

protected_hardlinks adds an extra unusual owner check for hard link creation,
may be it is too protective.

Until the latest nova/libvirt/libguestfs combination is not
protected_hardlinks friendly, it should be disabled.

See also: https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/sysctl/fs.txt

Change-Id: I9ea90e0b76e4be9d4bd9d722fd65244a3c114949
'}]
commit_message:
protected_hardlinks should be disabled

The newer libguestfs as it used by nova not compatible with the
hard link protection.

This option is disabled on most systems, but it is enabled on f19 by
default.

protected_hardlinks adds an extra unusual owner check for hard link creation,
may be it is too protective.

Until the latest nova/libvirt/libguestfs combination is not
protected_hardlinks friendly, it should be disabled.

See also: https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/sysctl/fs.txt

Change-Id: I9ea90e0b76e4be9d4bd9d722fd65244a3c114949
